Introduction:

In today’s digital age, having digital literacy is essential for students to succeed academically and professionally. As a Student Digital Ambassador, this project helped me understand the importance of using digital tools effectively, safely, and responsibly. The project included five different tasks covering areas such as awareness, professional online presence, coding platforms, communication skills, and cybercrime safety.

Through this project, I explored various platforms like GitHub, LinkedIn, HackerRank, and Google Forms. Each task provided practical experience in building skills that are important for students in the modern digital world. Overall, this project helped me become more confident in using technology for learning, communication, and career development.


Task 1 – Infographic: 

For Task 1, I created a digital literacy awareness infographic using Canva. Canva is an easy-to-use online design tool that provides various templates and elements for creating visually appealing content. My infographic focused on three main topics: the meaning of digital literacy, safe internet practices, and useful digital tools for students.

The infographic explained how digital literacy is not just about using technology, but also about understanding how to use it responsibly. I included tips such as using strong passwords, avoiding suspicious links, and maintaining a professional online presence. I also mentioned useful tools like Google Docs, GitHub, and LinkedIn.

One challenge I faced was selecting the right design and organizing the content in a clear and attractive way. However, it was also interesting to experiment with colors, icons, and layouts. This task helped me improve my creativity and understand how to communicate important information visually.


Task 2 – Digital Portfolio:

In Task 2, I created my digital portfolio by setting up profiles on GitHub, LinkedIn, and HackerRank. These platforms are widely used by students and professionals for learning, networking, and showcasing skills.

On GitHub, I created a profile README that includes my name, branch, and learning goals. GitHub is mainly used to store and share coding projects. On LinkedIn, I added my educational details such as my degree, college, and expected graduation year. LinkedIn helps in building a professional network and finding job or internship opportunities. I also created a HackerRank account to practice coding problems.

In the coming years, I plan to use GitHub to upload my projects, LinkedIn to connect with professionals, and HackerRank to improve my programming skills. This task made me realize the importance of maintaining a strong digital presence, which can help in career growth and opportunities.


Task 3 – Platforms: 

In this task, I explored both coding practice platforms and collaboration tools. I created an account on HackerRank and solved a beginner-level problem called “Solve Me First.” This helped me understand the basics of coding and problem-solving. It was a simple task, but it gave me confidence to start learning programming.

I also created a Google Form titled “Digital Literacy Awareness Quiz” with five questions. The form included both multiple-choice and short-answer questions. After creating the form, I linked it to Google Sheets to collect responses automatically.

These tools are very useful for students. Coding platforms like HackerRank help in improving logical thinking and programming skills, while Google Forms can be used for quizzes, surveys, and data collection. This task showed me how digital tools can make learning more interactive and efficient.


Task 4 – Email Etiquette: 

In this task, I learned the importance of professional communication through emails and social media. Poor communication can create misunderstandings and leave a bad impression. For example, if a student sends an email to a professor without a proper subject, greeting, or respectful tone, it may be ignored or misunderstood.

To avoid such situations, it is important to follow proper email etiquette, such as writing clear subject lines, using polite language, and structuring the message properly. I also created a social media checklist to guide responsible online behavior.

This task helped me understand that communication skills are just as important as technical skills. Writing clear and respectful messages can help build good relationships in both academic and professional environments.


Task 5 – Cybercrime: 

While working on this task, I learned about different types of cybercrimes such as phishing and online payment fraud. What surprised me the most was how easily people can be tricked into sharing sensitive information through fake messages or websites.

Many cybercrimes target students by sending links that appear genuine but are actually harmful. This made me realize the importance of being cautious while using the internet. One important habit I will change is that I will always verify links and avoid sharing personal or financial information online without proper verification.

This task increased my awareness about online safety and taught me how to protect myself and others from cyber threats.


Conclusion:-

Overall, this project was a valuable learning experience that improved my digital skills and awareness. I learned how to create content, build a professional online presence, use coding platforms, communicate effectively, and stay safe online. Each task provided practical knowledge that will be useful in my academic journey and future career.

As a Student Digital Ambassador, I now feel more confident in guiding others about digital tools and safe practices. This project helped me understand that digital literacy is an essential skill in today’s world.


